1 Introduction to Data Export API
Welcome to the Qu Data Export API. This document details the interfaces and standard use cases for integration
partners looking to leverage general data from Qu.
The Data Export API is a read-only API that enables partners to retrieve raw data for analytics and post-processing
for the following core data sets:
Check data to retrieve check-level data including:
Item sales
Service charges
Taxes
Payments
Voids and refunds
Configuration data to retrieve definitions and listings of major data sets including:
Menu item, portion, groupings and category details
Ancillary data for taxes, payments, service charges and location details
Employee data for job , payroll profile and labor hours
Till Reconciliation, Paid in/out, Over/Under data and other financial balancing data
Employee/Labor data for retrieving employee information and time clock data
The high level functions listed above encompass most of the currently available data, but more data points are
added frequently (or removed much less frequently) in any given release, so it is important to continually keep up
to date with release notes and check for changes to the data output.
Please reach out to partnersupport@qubeyond.com if there are any questions, comments or feedback on this
documentation.
1.1 Resources
1.1.1 Base URLs
Staging/Sandbox URL Production/Live URL
https://reporting-api-stg.qubeyond.com https://reporting-api.qubeyond.com
1.1.2 Request and response structure
The Qu API is organized around REST with predictable, resource-oriented URLs and HTTP response codes to
indicate API errors. Every request to Qu is comprised of HTTP Headers, endpoint URL and (for some requests) a
JSON Body. All JSON structures follow the rules specified in RFC4627; and are encoded as UTF8 as specified in
RFC3629 using one to four bytes per Unicode code point.
All responses return in JSON format and uses standard HTTP response codes for ease of development.
1.1.3 Required HTTP headers
All requests to Qu APIs must include the following headers:

Generating the X-Integration header
The X-Integration header should be set as the qu.uid of the decoded JWT token received when authenticating
for Qu services. This JWT is encoded via the HS256 algorithm. There are many resources and libraries available
online for decoding JWTs and parsing data, Qu recommends https://jwt.io/libraries as a starting point.

Authentication to the API is performed via OAuth. To perform requests, it is required to authenticate with the
credentials of a user that belongs to a company.

1.3 Endpoint and parameters
There is only 1 endpoint for the Data Export API, and all data requests are made using parameters to identify the
sub-type and filtering properties to receive.

companyId is the customer's unique account ID in Qu, which will always be the same for any given
location.
locationId is the unique location Id (store) for which the data will be retrieved. These location IDs can
be provided by the brand or Qu account representative or can be retrieved using the API itself.

1.3.1 Request parameters
There are several parameters that can be used for refining and filtering the data retrieved from the API. Not all
parameters are relevant to each scenario, a list of valid parameters will be provided in each major data section
along with best practices.
Parameter Description
GET /api/v3.5/export/{companyId}/{locationid}
The API access credentials provided will only work for a single customerId, but can be used for all
locationIds within that customerId.

data_type MANDATORY
Mandatory. Values: config, checks, labor, paid_inout, over_under, tills, desposits.
Specifies the type of data to export.
start_date Mandatory for checks, labor, paid_inout, over_under, and tills. Optional for

Start date of the export. Format: MMDDYYYY

sub_data_type Values: category, item_group, item, portion, void_reason, discount, tax,

Configuration data type can also be further categorized by different sub types,

delta_from_date
delta_from_time
Each response contains delta response parameters. If the next request contains
delta parameters instead of start_date and end_date then response will
contain data added since time defined in delta. Use for incremental export.
include_abandoned Values: true, false
Applies to: data_type=checks
IncludeAbandoned parameter is only used when requesting checks
(data_type=checks). When set to "true", the response will include all the checks
with state “Abandoned” for the requested location and date ranges.
All shifts, tills and checks that were left open by the employees will be processed
by an automatic task that runs everyday after the business hours of each
location. This process can be enabled or disabled depending on the customer
preferences.
Checks that are processed by this task are set to state "Abandoned".

output_structure Values: item_portion_unified / default
Applies to:
data_type=checks
data_type=config&sub_data_type=item
data_type=config&sub_data_type=item_group
The output_structure parameter was introduced to support the unify item-
portion id representation, on each configuration (item / item_group) and also
on the checks response.
In case we send a default or empty value the response will contain the items and
portions separately as usual .
When set the value as item_portion_unified it will return a combination of the
items and portions with a unique item id representing the item-portion id. In
this case the portion id won’t be exported and the name of the new item will
contain the portion description.
Consider the following example - an item “Mac & Cheese” with portions
“Regular” and “Large”The conversion consists in 3 steps:
For each Portion that “Mac & Cheese” had configured, a new individual item
was created.
A new unique ID is generated for each new item (this ID is only visible on the
API for now).
The names for the new items are a combination of the Item’s and its
Portion’s names.
Item: “Mac & Cheese”
Portion: “Regular”
New Item: “Mac & Cheese, Regular”
Combined names will be visible only when exporting 'config/item'. Exporting
'config/item_group' and 'checks' will show only the new ids. Also if the items
do not have portions they will be converted as well creating new item_ids.

2 Working with the Data Export API
The Data Export API is an extremely versatile API designed to be used for a variety of applications. Because of this,
rather than exhaustively try to identify each use case, this guide seeks to provide best practices and strategies for
the consumption of the data retrieved to get the most out of the functions.
As such, high level use cases for each major category have been created along with the spec itself. It is up to the
integrator to responsibly manipulate the data themselves as the exported data provided from this API is raw and
does not include summaries or aggregations.

Available Locations Data
Check Data
Configuration Data
Employee and Labor Data
Accounting Data

2.2 Check Data
Check data is generally the most crucial data set that integrators make use of. The Data Export API provides a raw
feed of check data with a custom set of parameters to further refine what can become a firehose of data.
2.2.1 Relevant parameters
Parameter Description
GET /api/v3.5/export/{customerid}/{locationid}?data_type=checks
Qu Data Export API
Integrations
Working with the Data Export API – 14
start_date
(Basic)
Specifies the starting point for the export. This will include all checks for this date and
onward until end_date (if applicable).
This is mandatory if not using the delta parameters.
Format: MMDDYYYY
end_date
(Basic)
Specifies the end date for the export. If applied this will be the end of the date range and
include all checks up to and including this date.
If end_date is not specified then the export will return all indexed checks up until the
moment that the request to the API was made.
Format: MMDDYYYY
delta_from_date
(Advanced)
These parameters should only be used when doing incremental export updates
throughout the day such as for integrators updating data live. If using delta parameters,
do not use the startDate and endDate parameters.
Format: MMDDYYYY / HHMM
delta_from_time
(Advanced)
include_abandoned
(Advanced)
IncludeAbandoned parameter is only used when requesting checks (data_type=checks).
When set to "true", the response will include all the checks with state “Abandoned” for
the requested location and date ranges.
All shifts, tills and checks that were left open by the employees will be processed by an
automatic task that runs everyday after the business hours of each location. This
process can be enabled or disabled depending on the customer preferences.
Checks that are processed by this task are set to state "Abandoned".
Format: true, false
Using the delta fields will return data that can be “volatile” in that the check
data could be altered after the initial polling and should always be reconciled
with a standard lookback request to ensure the data is complete.

2.2.5 Basic Check Data Strategies
While the check data can be manipulated in so many ways by the integrator, there are a few key strategies that are
recommended for basic check logging and analytics.
Basic check strategies are most relevant to integrators that:
Consume check data less frequently (once a day or less)
Do not use check sales data for intra-day reporting or “live” dashboards
Do not have specific considerations around portioning and inventory tracking
Do not track abandoned checks (a common item for loss prevention integrations)
Implementing a basic check data collection strategy
The basic use cases are generally:
Getting check data for a specific day
Getting check data for a range of time
Getting all checks since a date
In these cases the standard request formats will be:
Qu Data Export API
Integrations
Working with the Data Export API – 29

Scenario Request parameters
Single Day data_type=checks
start_date={MMDDYYYY}
end_date={MMDDYYYY}
Start and End date should be the same day in this scenario.
Date Range data_type=checks
start_date={MMDDYYYY}
end_date={MMDDYYYY}
Start and End date should be different in this scenario.
All Checks Since data_type=checks
start_date={MMDDYYYY}
Do not specify any end_date.
Things to know about this strategy
Checks retrieved on these dates will be for the entire day’s worth of checks.
If the current date is included or the parameter does not include a past date as the end date, then all checks
up until the moment of the request will be included.
Changes to check data after the fact
When requesting from a single date or a range of dates, the most recent “iteration” of the check data will always be
returned. This is an especially important concept to understand when dealing with both basic and advanced
strategies and is best illustrated with an example.
Scenario: a check is created on September 1st with 3 items. The following day (9/2), the check is re-opened and 2 of
the items are refunded. The day after that (9/3), the check is re-opened again and the last item is refunded, resulting
in a $0 check.
Using Strategy 1:
If the application fetches all checks for starting and ending date of 9/1: the check will have 3 items on
it and no refunds logged
If the application fetches all checks for starting and ending date of 9/2: the check will appear with a
refund of two items (and not including the 3rd item that was still settled)
If the application fetches all checks for the starting and ending date of 9/3: the check will appear with
the last item refunded
Using Strategy 2:
If the application fetches all checks for the range of 9/1 - 9/2: the check will appear with a refund of
two items (and not including the 3rd item that was still settled)
If the application fetches all checks for the range of 9/1 - 9/3: the check will appear with all items
refunded
Why is it like this?
When a check is created in the system, it is immediately saved to the cloud as is. When changes occur, a new version
of the check is published and the previous version is logged as a child data set within the check. This allows for
consistency in daily reporting so it is possible to look up a previous day and see what the exact conditions were at
the time of closing on that day, without conflating it with changes that occurred later on.

This scenario of a check being re-opened and refunded separately across 3 different days is an incredibly unlikely

check, and that the status can change over time based on the configuration of the given brand.
2.2.6 Advanced Check Data Strategies
While the check data can be manipulated in so many ways by the integrator, there are a few key strategies that are
recommended for basic check logging and analytics.
Advanced check strategies are most relevant to integrators that:
Consume check frequently throughout the day for semi-live reporting, analytics or insights
Use item data from checks to inform inventory management platforms
Especially where there are portion-specific “recipes” mapped on the current IMS design
Track abandoned checks (a common item for loss prevention integrations)
Implementing advanced check data collection strategies by use case
Get incremental check data throughout the day
The Qu Data Export API does not currently support data-streaming, so all intra-day updates have to be polled from
the integrator-side. While there are no hard limits on the frequency, It is generally recommended to set this cadence
to no more than every 15 minutes, even for live dashboards as there’s diminishing returns on the relevance of the
telemetry, and shorter frequencies can lead to other issues as checks are most likely to be reopened and edited
within the first 10 minutes of ordering, and significantly less after that.
No matter the frequency, the way to get incremental check data throughout the day is to use the delta_from_date
and delta_from_time properties instead of the standard startDate and endDate properties.
Scenario Request parameters Result
Placing a request at 2:00PM
on October 1st for checks
from the last 15 minutes
data_type=checks
delta_from_date={10012022}
delta_from_time={1345}

A list of checks between 1:45PM
and the current moment (2:00PM).
Placing a request at 2:00PM
on October 1st for checks
from the last 5 DAYS
data_type=checks
delta_from_date={09262022}
delta_from_time={1400}
A list of checks starting at 2:00PM
on September 26th and going up to
the current moment (2:00PM)
It is highly recommended that any integrator that consumes check data for use that includes tracking the
voiding or refunding of checks implement ”lookback” logic that retrieves historical check data from a
period of multiple previous days with logic to overwrite previously stored check data if it is found there are
changes to the check. Failure to do so will result in erroneous final data collection.

The second scenario above, while possible, is highly discouraged as it will return all check data changes
within that time period which could return multiple instances of checks and have other inconsistent
results. For anything that spans more than a day, the proper use should be the basic start and end
date format from the basic check strategy.

Set up custom IDs for portion-specific recipes
Many brands make use of Qu portions, which exist as a property of the item itself and not as an actual item. For
example a small soda is simple a soda with the portion property of small. The small portion can then be re-used for
any item, not just sodas. This can present challenges for integrators that maintain atomic portioned items in their
database for reference as there is no uniqueness to the Item Master ID provided or the portion used.
As a way to make this transition easier, Qu has a parameter that allows for the specification of items x portions as
unique IDs so that they can be mapped uniquely on the receiving database rather than through parsing logic.
When the parameter “output_structure” is set to item_portion_unified, the returned item data will have
automatically generated IDs for all item x portion combinations in the check data which can then be directly related
to the recipe on the integrator side.
Here’s an example with the default item output as compared to the item_portion_unified option.

Track abandoned checks
Abandoned checks are defined within Qu as a check that has been started and has content on it but has not been
paid for by the time the end of day report is run. When the EOD process runs, it will force any unpaid checks into the
abandoned state to remove them from the suspended check list so that no checks remain unaccounted for in the
check data.
How are abandoned checks created?
These checks are created when a check is suspended by the cashier, either as a “shortcut” to voiding all the items
on an order cancelled before being fully paid or as a way to put a check aside while a guest goes to do something
else such as get their wallet from the car. Occasionally it can also indicate training issues or worse, theft, since the
check can still be sent to the kitchen for processing.
By default, abandoned checks are filtered out in the Data API export or in Qu’s EI reporting views as they do not
count as paid and closed checks. To keep them in results, include the parameter “include_abandoned=true” in the
API request.
The use of this parameter to generate these unique IDs is consistent and will not change over time for any
specific item x portion mapping unless one of those IDs is altered.
However the ID is not currently available for review within the Qu platform, the structure only exists in the
Data Export API translation layer.

2.4 Employee and Labor Data
Employee and Labor data is used primarily by HRIS systems to pull relevant employee information as well as clock
in/out records and breaks. This read-only data is often used in conjunction with the Qu Labor API to allow employee
management functions and tracking.
2.4.1 Employee
A Qu Employee object contains relevant data for each employee for the given location. This includes specific job
titles and payroll profiles for the given location.
Qu does not store high-risk PII such as SSN or EIN and in fact it is encouraged to limit the amount of PII that is
provided for integration partners that use the Qu Labor API to manage employees outside of the Qu platform.
GET /api/v3.5/export/{customerid}/{locationid}?data_type=config&sub_data_type=employee

2.4.2 Payroll Profile
The Payroll Profile is a reusable object in the Qu system that defines how wages are calculated for each employee
for a given job. For systems that rely on Qu-originated wage and clock in/out records, the Payroll Profile is one of
the most important pieces to reconciling that information.
Payroll profile object
Attribute Type Description
id long 
name string 
payroll_type string A mandatory identifier used for grouping payroll
profiles. Can be 1 of 4 types:
Hourly, with overtime
Hourly, no overtime
Salaried, with overtime
Salaried, no overtime
calculate_weekly bool Whether the employee’s hours have a weekly limit
before overtime applies.
weekly_hours int Hours allowed per week before overtime kicks in.
calculate_daily bool Whether the employee’s hours have a daily limit
before overtime applies.
daily_hours int Hours allowed per day before overtime kicks in.
double_daily_hours int Hours allowed per day before double overtime
kicks in.
overtime_multiplier decimal Multiplier applied to wage for overtime worked.
double_overtime_multiplier decimal Multiplier applied to wage for double overtime
worked.
min_paid_break int Minimum time to start paid break

2.4.3 Employee Labor Data
Employee Labor data provides the output of work tracked across the time period specified.
Relevant parameters
Parameter Description
start_date
(Basic)
Specifies the starting point for the export. This will include all employee and labor data
for this date and onward until end_date (if applicable).
This is mandatory if not using the delta parameters.
Format: MMDDYYYY
end_date
(Basic)
Specifies the end date for the export. If applied this will be the end of the date range and
include all employee and labor data up to and including this date.
If end_date is not specified then the export will return all indexed employee and labor
data up until the moment that the request to the API was made.
Format: MMDDYYYY
delta_from_date
(Advanced)
These parameters should only be used when doing incremental export updates
throughout the day such as for integrators updating data live. If using delta parameters,
do not use the startDate and endDate parameters.
delta_from_time
(Advanced)

could be altered after the initial polling and should always be reconciled with a
standard lookback request to ensure the information is complete.

2.5.2 Deposits
Store managers create deposits to declare cash that was extracted from the store and deposited in the bank. Each
cash deposit is linked to a list of reconciled tills. Deposits can be edited and deleted in EI.
Relevant parameters
Parameter Description
start_date

Specifies the starting point for the export. This will include all deposit data created on
this date and onward until end_date (if applicable).
Format: MMDDYYYY
end_date

Specifies the end date for the export. If applied this will be the end of the date range and
include all deposit data created up to and including this date.
If end_date is not specified then the export will return all indexed deposit data up until
the moment that the request to the API was made.
Format: MMDDYYYY
Deposit object
Attribute Type Additional Information
id string The cash deposit id
GET /api/v3.5/export/{customerid}/{locationid}?data_type=deposits
Qu Data Export API
Integrations
Working with the Data Export API – 73
date_time_deposit string The date and time when the deposit was made at the
bank, according to the employee adding the deposit
entry.
Format: yyyy-MM-ddTHH:mm:ss (Store Local Time)
date_time_created string The date and time when the deposit was created in Qu.
This is the date used by the request start and end date
filters.
Format: yyyy-MM-ddTHH:mm:ss (Store Local Time)
deposit_number string Reference number provided by the user

the deposit
tills Collection of
till_id (string)
List of reconciled tills that were linked to this deposit
Created Date vs. Deposit Date
The Qu system lists deposits based on the date of creation in the system, not the date of the actual deposit to the
bank. This is because deposits may be made to the bank in non-consecutive days and requires user entry to
confirm. For example, some businesses may add the deposits the next day everyday except Sunday, and some may
log them right before the end of a pay period. This is important to note as the parameters for start and end date
will return the deposits created in the time period, not necessarily the deposits made in that time period.

2.5.3 Over/Under Data
Over/Under data provides the difference in expected cash till and payments vs. the actual recorded over a period of
time.
GET /api/v3.5/export/{customerid}/{locationid}?data_type=over_under
Qu Data Export API
Integrations

Parameter Description
start_date
(Basic)
Specifies the starting point for the export. This will include all employee and labor data

This is mandatory if not using the delta parameters.
Format: MMDDYYYY
end_date
(Basic)
Specifies the end date for the export. If applied this will be the end of the date range and
include all employee and labor data up to and including this date.
If end_date is not specified then the export will return all indexed employee and labor
